{"title_page": "George Dickie (botanist)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\nProf '''George Dickie''' MD  {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|FRS|FLS}} (1812, [[Aberdeen]] \u2013 1882) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[botanist]], who specialised in [[algae]].\n\n==Life==\n[[File:The grave of Prof George Dickie, St Machar's Cathedral.jpg|thumb|The grave of Prof George Dickie, St Machar's Cathedral]]\nHe studied arts, then medicine at the [[University of Aberdeen|Universities of Aberdeen]] and [[University of Edinburgh|Edinburgh]]. He qualified as a doctor around 1835. In 1837 he is listed as a surgeon, living at Cherryvale in [[Aberdeen]].<ref>Aberdeen Post Office directory 1837</ref>\n\nHe became a lecturer on botany in King's College, Aberdeen, then University Librarian. In 1849 he was appointed the first Professor of Natural History at Queen's College, Belfast and became a Member of the [[Belfast Natural History Society]]. In 1860 he returned to Aberdeen University as [[Regius Professor of Botany (Aberdeen)|Regius Professor of Botany]]. He was succeeded in 1877 by Prof [[James William Helenus Trail]] FRS.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1111/j.1469-8137.1920.tb07316.x| title=James William Helenus Trail, M.a., M.d., F.r.s., F.l.s| journal=New Phytologist| volume=19| issue=1\u20132| pages=46\u201348| year=1920}}</ref>\n\nDickie worked, most importantly on the range and depth of marine algae and on cataloguing material brought back from the [[Challenger expedition]].\n\nDickie was a Fellow of the [[Linnean Society]] (1863), a Fellow of the [[Royal Society]] (1881) and a Member of the [[Belfast Natural History Society]].\n\nIn later life he lived at 16 Albyn Terrace in Aberdeen.<ref>Aberdeen Post Office Directory 1881</ref>\n\nHe died on 18 July 1882<ref>Grave of Prof Dickie, St Machars</ref> at is buried in the churchyard of [[St Machar's Cathedral]] in [[Old Aberdeen]]. The grave lies south west of the church.\n\nHe was succeeded by Prof [[James W. H. Trail]].<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1080/03746608609468214|title = George Dickie, M.D|journal = Transactions of the Botanical Society of Edinburgh|volume = 16|issue = 1\u20134|pages = 1\u20136|year = 1886}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\n\nHe was married to Agnes Willamson Low (d.1909).\n\n==Botanical Reference==\n\n{{Botanist|Dickie|Dickie}}\n\n== References ==\n*{{cite DNB|wstitle=Dickie, George}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.algaebase.org/search/bibliography/ Algaebase] Bibliography.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dickie, George}}\n[[Category:1812 births]]\n[[Category:1882 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:19th-century British botanists]]\n[[Category:Scottish botanists]]\n[[Category:Scottish naturalists]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:British phycologists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Scottish scholars and academics]]\n[[Category:Academics of Queen's University Belfast]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Society]]\n[[Category:19th-century Scottish medical doctors]]\n[[Category:Scottish librarians]]\n[[Category:Scottish marine biologists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Linnean Society of London]]\n\n\n{{Scotland-med-bio-stub}}\n{{Scotland-botanist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\nProf '''George Dickie''' MD  {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|FRS|FLS}} (1812, [[Aberdeen]] \u2013 1882) was a [[Scotland|Scottish]] [[botanist]], who specialised in [[algae]].\n\n==Life==\n[[File:The grave of Prof George Dickie, St Machar's Cathedral.jpg|thumb|The grave of Prof George Dickie, St Machar's Cathedral]]\nHe studied arts, then medicine at the Universities of Aberdeen and Edinburgh. He qualified as a doctor around 1835. In 1837 he is listed as a surgeon, living at Cherryvale in [[Aberdeen]].<ref>Aberdeen Post Office directory 1837</ref>\n\nHe became a lecturer on botany in King's College, Aberdeen, then University Librarian. In 1849 he was appointed the first Professor of Natural History at Queen's College, Belfast and became a Member of the [[Belfast Natural History Society]]. In 1860 he returned to Aberdeen University as [[Regius Professor of Botany (Aberdeen)|Regius Professor of Botany]]. He was succeeded in 1877 by Prof [[James William Helenus Trail]] FRS.<ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1111/j.1469-8137.1920.tb07316.x| title=James William Helenus Trail, M.a., M.d., F.r.s., F.l.s| journal=New Phytologist| volume=19| issue=1\u20132| pages=46\u201348| year=1920}}</ref>\n\nDickie worked, most importantly on the range and depth of marine algae and on cataloguing material brought back from the [[Challenger expedition]].\n\nDickie was a Fellow of the [[Linnean Society]] (1863), a Fellow of the [[Royal Society]] (1881) and a Member of the [[Belfast Natural History Society]].\n\nIn later life he lived at 16 Albyn Terrace in Aberdeen.<ref>Aberdeen Post Office Directory 1881</ref>\n\nHe died on 18 July 1882<ref>Grave of Prof Dickie, St Machars</ref> at is buried in the churchyard of [[St Machar's Cathedral]] in [[Old Aberdeen]]. The grave lies south west of the church.\n\nHe was succeeded by Prof [[James W. H. Trail]].<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1080/03746608609468214|title = George Dickie, M.D|journal = Transactions of the Botanical Society of Edinburgh|volume = 16|issue = 1\u20134|pages = 1\u20136|year = 1886}}</ref>\n\n==Family==\n\nHe was married to Agnes Willamson Low (d.1909).\n\n==Botanical Reference==\n\n{{Botanist|Dickie|Dickie}}\n\n== References ==\n*{{cite DNB|wstitle=Dickie, George}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.algaebase.org/search/bibliography/ Algaebase] Bibliography.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dickie, George}}\n[[Category:1812 births]]\n[[Category:1882 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Scottish people]]\n[[Category:19th-century British botanists]]\n